Lessons that can be learned today from the Cuban Missile Crisis
“Thirteen Days” (”Thirteen Days”), a new film about the Cuban Missile Crisis, will soon be released in cinemas across many countries.
Everyone should see this work, not only because the film deals with the past, but also because it offers insights into current events – particularly with regard to the controversies surrounding a US national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy called his closest advisors together in the White House.
Aerial photographs of the region had revealed the construction of a stationing of atomic weapons on Cuba.
Decisions made in the following 13 days and decisions that could not be made might have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what happened during these days in the White House.
Tape recordings made during the presidency of Kennedy played a significant role in the creation of the film.
Following the film's premiere in the United States, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard initiated a discussion round, which should discuss the film and the crisis it deals with.
Participants in this round included, among others: Robert McNamara, U.S. Secretary of Defense under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter of Kennedy’s; Ernest R. May, a Harvard history professor who has written a book about the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a Harvard professor of political science, who presented his classic study of the Cuban Missile Crisis, "The Essence of Decision", 30 years ago.
Furthermore, Peter A. Almond, the film's producer, was present.
Although the film treatment of the subject was criticized in various points, the participants in the discussion were able to agree that the film depicts the problems and the pressure with which President Kennedy was confronted exactly as they were in reality.
What conclusions can be drawn from the Cuban Crisis today?
Theodore Sorensen summarized them as follows:
• Advisers must play their role in the event of a crisis, but it is solely the President who ultimately has to bear the responsibility.
Most of Kennedy's advisors – both civil and military – wanted to attack Cuba back then.
Only through Kennedy's sober analysis and his probing questions could alternatives and dangers be shown, which were crucial in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how an opponent thinks; in addition, the lines of communication must be kept open.
Pushing an opponent into a corner without keeping diplomatic channels open, which allow you to understand the opponent's situation, could prove disastrous.
· The United States relies on allies.
Kennedy acted this way because the NATO, other allies, and the opinion of the world had supported him.
A certain period of time is necessary for a meeting of good decisions.
When it comes to life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to push him into an action.
The fact that a week went by in which all involved factors were examined and weighed in the most precise manner was decisive for the outcome.
However, would such a time frame for weighing things even exist today in the face of the currently existing mass media?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it is necessary to put oneself in the position of the opponent.
In one of the scenes heavily criticized in the film, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade imposed by Kennedy over Cuba was primarily intended to send a signal to Soviet President Khrushchev about Kennedy's intentions, and not as a means to stop certain Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted even more leniently?
After all, the US had also stationed nuclear warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station rockets on Cuba only reflected this policy.
Kennedy, however, showed concern regarding the consequences of the stationing of Soviet missiles in Cuba in relation to Berlin.
The pressure of nuclear weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
Ultimately, "the Berlin crisis was resolved by the results of the Cuban crisis," as historian Ernest May claimed.
"It will soon be too late," was a widely circulated argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
Advisors wanted to attack Cuba while the missiles, as they assumed – were on their way to Cuba by sea.
There was an approximately 180,000-man US troop force prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a lightning bombardment that would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack in Kosovo sixty years later. “I needed thirty years,” McNamara said, “to find out that there were already nuclear weapons on Cuba: 162 warheads, and of those 90 were strategic nuclear warheads.”
McNamara received this information during a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He put the following three questions to Castro: 1) Did you know about it?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
3) What would the consequences have been for Cuba?
Castro replied: "I knew the facts.
And I explicitly recommended that atomic weapons be used.
I knew this would have led to the extermination of Cuba.”
Castro and – to a greater extent – his comrade Che Guevara were willing to let Cuba go up in smoke so that their country would become a martyr in the struggle for world revolution!
A invasion would have had the consequence of the death of 80 million US-Americans and the destruction of Cuba, only because the Kennedy government lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (which occurs more often when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is of the firm conviction that an invasion would "undoubtedly" have led to a Soviet nuclear attack against the USA.
Chruschtschow's control over the Soviet military on Cuba was, however, limited: U2 aircraft flying over Cuban airspace were fired upon, despite explicit contrary instructions from the Chairman.
A difficult question to answer, which did not arise during this debate in Harvard, is the following: what would have happened if the opponent had not been Chruschtschow, who has shown himself during the crisis more by a rational behavior, but an opponent of the type of Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il or a fundamentalist?
In view of the spread of nuclear weapons, this danger could one day become a reality.
Today's discussions about a limited missile defense and the threat of nuclear blackmail by rogue states should be conducted in the light of this terrifying, but by no means unrealistic thought.
Harvard has put a new web-site on the internet, where the main documents about the Cuban crisis as well as the current nuclear threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org .
